<p>printf() function, like i Said, prints leading ffffff (technically I understand that most significant bit carries sign so it gets carried all the way to where data starts). But how to get rid of them I have no idea. I read doc-s on printf() tried and tried and tried, ate some ice-cream and tried again. Here is what I have:</p>  <pre><code>int mem_display(Cmd *cp, char *arguments) {   int i;   char *adr;   int w = 0;   w = sscanf(arguments,"%x",&amp;adr);   printf("sscan returned = %d\n",w);   printf("%#0.8s ",arguments);    for (i=0; i&lt;16; i++) {     printf("%02.x ",(unsigned int)*(adr+i));   } ... </code></pre>  <p>the output:</p>  <pre><code> % UNIX-tutor&gt; md 10668  /*calling function show memory location 0x10668*/     OUT:     sscan returned = 1      10668 ffffffbc 10 20 ffffffe0 ffffffa0 40 ffffffa2 ffffffa0 44 ffffff9c 23 ffffffa0 20 </code></pre>  <p>solved:</p>  <pre><code>printf("%0.2x ",(unsigned int)*(adr+i)); </code></pre>  <p>output:</p>  <pre><code>UNIX-tutor&gt; md 10000 sscan returned = 1  10000 7f 45 4c 46 01 02 01 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 .ELF............ </code></pre>